SIMPLE: interlace
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interlace
<hw>In`ter*lace"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interlaced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Interlacing</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>entrelacen</ets>, F.
<ets>entrelacer</ets>. See <er>Inter-</er>, and <er>Lace</er>.]</ety>
<def>To unite, as by lacing together; to insert or interpose one thing
within another; to intertwine; to interweave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Severed into stripes⟦br⟧
That <qex>interlaced</qex> each other.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The epic way is everywhere <qex>interlaced</qex> with
dialogue.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Interlacing arches</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>,
<cd>arches, usually circular, so constructed that their archivolts
intersect and seem to be interlaced.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interlacement</ent>⟦br⟧
